# Apex Coding Standards

## Trigger Framework

Every trigger in this project follows the single-trigger-per-object dispatcher pattern:

- **One trigger per SObject.** Never create a second trigger on an object that already has one.
- **Trigger file is thin:** delegates immediately to `GenericTriggerDispatcher`.
- **Handler class** implements `ITriggerHandler` and contains all business logic.
- Handler class naming: `[ObjectName]TriggerHandler` (e.g., `LoyaltyProgramMemberTriggerHandler`).

```apex
// Correct pattern
trigger LoyaltyProgramMemberTrigger on LoyaltyProgramMember (
    before insert, before update, after insert, after update
) {
    GenericTriggerDispatcher.run(new LoyaltyProgramMemberTriggerHandler());
}
```

No business logic in the trigger file itself.

## Bulkification (Non-Negotiable)

- **Never** place SOQL or DML inside a `for` loop — this is a Critical defect.
- Collect IDs and keys in a loop; run one query outside the loop.
- Collect records to insert/update/delete in a list; run one DML statement outside the loop.

```apex
// Correct
Set<Id> memberIds = new Set<Id>();
for (TransactionJournal tj : Trigger.new) {
    memberIds.add(tj.LoyaltyProgramMemberId);
}
Map<Id, LoyaltyProgramMember> members = new Map<Id, LoyaltyProgramMember>(
    [SELECT Id, [PROJECT_FIELD__c] FROM LoyaltyProgramMember WHERE Id IN :memberIds]
);
```

## FLS / CRUD Enforcement

- Use `Security.stripInaccessible(AccessType.READABLE, records)` before returning query results to UI.
- Use `Security.stripInaccessible(AccessType.CREATABLE/UPDATABLE, records)` before DML in user context.
- Use `WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED` in SOQL for user-context queries where stripInaccessible is not used.
- System-context bypasses (e.g., `without sharing`) must be commented with justification.

## Naming Conventions

| Element | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Class | PascalCase | `AccountService`, `OrderEventBuilder` |
| Trigger handler | `[Object]TriggerHandler` | `AccountTriggerHandler`, `OrderTriggerHandler` |
| Method | camelCase, verb-first | `processRecords()`, `buildPayload()` |
| Constant | UPPER_SNAKE_CASE | `MAX_RETRY_COUNT` |
| Test class | `[ClassName]Test` | `AccountServiceTest` |
| Custom exception | `[Name]Exception extends Exception` | `IntegrationException` |
| Custom field (Apex ref) | Use API name | `[PROJECT_FIELD__c]` (e.g., `Status__c`, `ExternalId__c`) |

## SOQL Best Practices

- Use bind variables (`WHERE Id IN :idSet`). Never concatenate user input into dynamic SOQL.
- Always include `LIMIT` on queries that could return unbounded rows.
- Prefer relationship queries over multiple flat queries.
- For loyalty objects, prefer the Business APIs (`loyalty.*`) over raw SOQL + DML where available.

## Null Handling

- **Prefer the null coalescing operator (`??`)** over explicit `!= null` ternaries for default values ([Apex docs](https://developer.salesforce.com/docs/atlas.en-us.apexcode.meta/apexcode/langCon_apex_NullCoalescingOperator.htm)).
- Use `?.` (safe navigation) to traverse nullable chains without intermediate null checks.
- Combine both for concise, readable null handling.

```apex
// Preferred — null coalescing + safe navigation
String region = member.Partner_Geographic_Area__c ?? 'US';
String partnerName = linkedPartner?.LoyaltyProgramPartner?.Name ?? 'Unknown';
Integer retryCount = config?.Max_Retries__c?.intValue() ?? 3;

// Avoid — verbose ternary
String region = member.Partner_Geographic_Area__c != null
    ? member.Partner_Geographic_Area__c : 'US';
```

- **When to use `??`:** Assigning a fallback/default when a value might be null.
- **When NOT to use `??`:** When null means "skip processing" rather than "use default" — use an explicit `if (x != null)` guard instead.

## Collection & Loop Efficiency (Non-Negotiable)

- **Build Maps upfront, then do lookups — never iterate a second collection inside a loop.**
- When you need to correlate two datasets, build a `Map<Key, Value>` from one collection *before* iterating the other.
- This prevents O(n*m) complexity from nested iteration and reduces CPU time at scale.

```apex
// CORRECT — Map built upfront, O(n + m) total
Map<Id, LoyaltyProgramPartner> partnerMap = new Map<Id, LoyaltyProgramPartner>(
    [SELECT Id, Name, Partner_Code__c FROM LoyaltyProgramPartner WHERE Id IN :partnerIds]
);

for (LoyaltyPgmMbrLinkedPtnr link : linkedPartners) {
    LoyaltyProgramPartner partner = partnerMap.get(link.LoyaltyProgramPartnerId);
    if (partner != null) {
        link.Description = 'Linked to ' + partner.Name;
    }
}
```

```apex
// WRONG — nested iteration, O(n*m), governor-hostile at scale
for (LoyaltyPgmMbrLinkedPtnr link : linkedPartners) {
    for (LoyaltyProgramPartner partner : allPartners) {
        if (partner.Id == link.LoyaltyProgramPartnerId) {
            link.Description = 'Linked to ' + partner.Name;
            break;
        }
    }
}
```

**Rules:**
- If you query related records, immediately put them in a `Map<Id, SObject>` or `Map<String, SObject>`.
- Never search a `List` linearly for a matching record — use a Map lookup.
- When processing trigger context, build Maps from `Trigger.oldMap` / `Trigger.newMap` rather than iterating `Trigger.old` inside `Trigger.new` loops.
- For multi-key correlations (e.g., match on MembershipNumber + PartnerCode), use a composite key: `Map<String, SObject>` with key = `memberId + '|' + partnerCode`.

## Error Handling

- Wrap DML and callout operations in `try/catch`.
- Log exceptions to the project's designated exception log object (see org-context.md) — do not silently swallow errors.
- Use `Database.insert(list, false)` with `SaveResult` inspection when partial success is valid.
- Remove `System.debug` statements from production code paths before commit.

## Async Patterns

- `@future`: `static void`, primitive/collection params only, no SObject arguments.
- `Queueable`: implement `Database.AllowsCallouts` when making callouts.
- Never call `System.enqueueJob()` inside a loop.
- `Batch`: default scope 200; reduce to 50–100 for memory-intensive operations.
- Prefer Platform Events for decoupled, event-driven integration over synchronous callouts (see org-context.md for project-specific Platform Event API names).

## Loyalty Management Patterns

- **Business APIs over raw DML:** Use `loyalty.LoyaltyEngineInput`, `loyalty.MemberPointsInput`, etc. instead of direct DML on `TransactionJournal`, `LoyaltyLedger`, or `LoyaltyMemberCurrency`.
- **Platform Event publishing:** Use `EventBus.publish()` in dedicated publisher classes (e.g., `[PROJECT]EventPublisher`); implement `EventBus.EventPublishFailureCallback` for failure scenarios.
- **Custom ID allocation:** If the project uses custom ID pools (e.g., `[PROJECT_ID_POOL__c]`), always use the designated allocation logic — never generate or format IDs manually.
- **Recursion guard:** Loyalty operations can re-trigger member updates. Ensure `LoyaltyProgramMemberTriggerHandler` (and any related handlers) have a recursion guard (static boolean or counter).

## Test Class Requirements

- Annotate with `@isTest`.
- Use `@TestSetup` for shared test data.
- **Bulk test required:** At least one test method must insert/update 200+ records.
- **Negative test required:** At least one test validates error conditions or null input.
- Assertions must have meaningful messages: `System.assertEquals(expected, actual, 'Description of what failed')`.
- `Test.startTest()` / `Test.stopTest()` wrapping async invocations.
- `Test.setMock()` for all callout tests.
- No `SeeAllData=true` without explicit justification in a comment.
- `System.runAs(user)` for permission-sensitive scenarios.
